{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620497"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:43:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:43:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16631"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16631"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.14,0.52,0.21,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76353"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9322"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61862"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5305"},{"type":"tags","id":"10145"},{"type":"tags","id":"10146"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22381"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76353"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe contraceptive vaginal ring is a flexible plastic ring that provides hormonal contraception through vaginal absorption.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Releases copper ions to prevent implantation","Creates a physical barrier preventing sperm entry","Releases combined hormones to inhibit ovulation","Releases progestogen only to thicken cervical mucus","Releases spermicide to kill sperm cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe contraceptive vaginal ring \u003Cstrong\u003Ereleases combined hormones (ethinylestradiol and etonogestrel) to inhibit ovulation\u003C/strong\u003E. The hormones are continuously absorbed through the vaginal mucosa over three weeks, suppressing the hypothalamic-pituitary axis to prevent ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ring does not \u003Cstrong\u003Erelease copper ions to prevent implantation\u003C/strong\u003E - copper intrauterine devices are an alternative method of contraception that prevent implantation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ring does not function as a barrier method and therefore cannot \u003Cstrong\u003Ecreate a physical barrier preventing sperm entry\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ring is a combined hormonal contraceptive method, and therefore the option \u0027\u003Cstrong\u003Ereleases progestogen only to thicken cervical mucus\u0027\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ring does not \u003Cstrong\u003Erelease spermicide to kill sperm cells\u003C/strong\u003E. No spermicidal agents are present in the device.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vaginal route of administration allows for lower hormone doses compared to oral contraceptives as it bypasses first-pass metabolism in the liver. The ring is used for three weeks followed by a one-week ring-free interval.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The contraceptive vaginal ring releases both ethinylestradiol and etonogestrel continuously over three weeks.","The vaginal ring works primarily by inhibiting ovulation through negative feedback on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis.","The vaginal route allows for lower hormone doses compared to oral contraceptives due to bypass of first-pass metabolism."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61862"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16631"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61862"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T09:05:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T09:06:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9322"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76353"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remembe